 is more meaningful with real friends and colleagues. It means one isn't having to work hard at being popular all the time (in order to avoid being bullied). &#10;As home educators we have more opportunity to explore the world than those unfortunates who are confined to school grounds all day. &#10;The social environment within schools is far from ideal and very different from the rest of society. It is thus no kind of preparation for life. Bullying, disruption, an authoritarian curriculum and continual testing don't make for an atmosphere which fosters cooperation and learning. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="881" language="en" documentId="1038" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="RonTom" date="07 November 2009 4:06pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6755566" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="5" thumbsDown="0" origId="1038" notes="" title="Ridiculous rules for home schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="114"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="115" end="461"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="462" end="594"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="595" end="881"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51"/></xmi:XMI>